 from Middle English <i>dancer</i>, <i>dauncer</i> ‘dancer, especially a professional public dancer’ from an agent derivative of Middle English <i>dancen</i>, <i>dauncen</i> ‘to dance’ (compare   Dance  ).","Altered form of Dutch   Danser   or German   Danzer  , cognates of English <b>Dancer</b> (see 1 above)."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":3,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705183,"age":23,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705184,"age":33,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Robert d'Anver II was born as the son of Robert d'Anvers I and Mrs Robert d'Anvers. He had at least 1 son. He died after 1180, in Cheshire, England."},"et":{"–after 1180":"–pärast 1180","1135–1197":"1135–1197","–1180":"–1180","1180–1240":"1180–1240","1109–Male":"1109–Surnud","1112–Female":"1112–Surnud","after 1180":"pärast 1180","before 1135":"enne 1135","1135":"1135","1112":"1112","1066":"1066","1197":"1197","1086":"1086","1240":"1240","1096":"1096","1109":"1109","1180":"1180","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","England":"England"},"fi":{"–after 1180":"–1180 jälkeen","1135–1197":"1135–1197","–1180":"–1180","1180–1240":"1180–1240","1109–Male":"1109–Kuollut","1112–Female":"1112–Kuollut","after 1180":"1180 jälkeen","before 1135":"ennen vuotta 1135","1135":"1135","1112":"1112","1066":"1066","1197":"1197","1086":"1086","1240":"1240","1096":"1096","1109":"1109","1180":"1180","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","England":"England"},"fr":{"–after 1180":"–après 1180","1135–1197":"1135–1197","–1180":"–1180","1180–1240":"1180–1240","1109–Male":"1109–Décédé","1112–Female":"1112–Décédée","after 1180":"après 1180","before 1135":"avant 1135","1135":"1135","1112":"1112","1066":"1066","1197":"1197","1086":"1086","1240":"1240","1